Before getting into Matthew chapter 5, let's do a quick recap of where we're coming from in chapter 4

In chapter 4 verses 1-11, Matthew outlines Jesus' victory over satan as he fasts for 40 days in the wilderness and resists multiple temptations 

Verses 12-17 mark the beginning of Jesus' ministry where be begins preaching publicly, repeating John the baptists urgent message to repent for the kingdom of heaven is near

In verses 18-22 We learn about the recruitment of Jesus' first 4 disciples. 2 pairs of brothers who are fishermen in Galilee: Peter and Andrew, James and John

and in verses 23-25 we read about Jesus preaching the word of God and healing all kinds of diseases and afflictions


So at this point, awareness of Jesus is spreading and begins drawing massive crowds of people who are coming to hear Jesus' teachings and witness his miracles


That brings us to chapter 5 which is perhaps the most famous and significant sermon given by Jesus known as sermon on the mount where he shares the beatitudes

I'm going to walk through each of the Beatitudes one at a time because while they are simple and short, they hold profound meaning so I want to unpack them individually

---> Verses 1-3


Beatitude comes from the latin word beatus which means blessed, happy or fortunate

To be blessed means to experience divine favour. To be favoured by God

To have profound inner joy and contentment that is independent of external circumstances

Simply put, to be blessed means to experience joy and to be favoured by God. Doesn't necessarily mean to be happy

Through the beatitudes, Jesus is describing the character, attitudes and circumstances of people who experience God's favour and true flourishing in his kingdom

Jesus begins with saying that those who are poor in spirit will receive the kingdom of heaven

What does it mean to be poor in spirit?

Spiritual humility. A recognition of our spiritual bankruptcy and need for his grace

THose who are poor in spirit recognize their dependence on God rather than self righteousness. Being poor in spirit counters pride and the false notion of self sufficiency


---> Verse 4: "Blessed are those who mourn, for they shall be comforted"

Those who mourn (feel sorrow or grief) sin (our own sin,, the worlds sin) and brokenness of the world will be met with deep comfort instead of superficial happiness

Those who experience grief over the state of the world or the evil they witness will be comforted by God


---> Verse 5: Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth

Meekness isn't weakness. It means gentle strength under self control

Meekness describes power restrained by humility

People who don't grasp at or strive for power will inherit the earth


---> Verse 6: Blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they shall be satisfied.

Those with a deep longing for justice, holiness and correct relationships with God and others 

Those who strive for righteousness will be satisfied. Will be nourished and cared for by God


---> Verse 7: Blessed are the merciful, for they shall receive mercy.

TO be merciful means to be compassionate, forgiving and kind

Those who show mercy to others will receive God's mercy when it's their time to be judged 

Showing mercy to the underserving is to embody God's character


---> Verse 8: "Blessed are the pure in heart, for they shall see God.

To be pure in hear means to focus purely, 100% on God, inside and out. In our hearts and in our actions

Jesus is saying that when the kingdom of heaven arrives, those who are pure in their devotion to God will see him


---> verse 9: Blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall be called sons of God.

To be a peacemaker means to actively pursue reconciliation and peace with others. Even those who have wronged us

To work persistently towards the resolution of conflict


---> verse 10: Blessed are those who are persecuted for righteousness ' sake, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.

Those who do the right thing and are punished or persecuted because of it will be offered the Kingdom of heaven as their reward

People who choose the righteous path despite threat of persecution within their earthly life will be rewarded with the gift of heaven


---> verse 11: Blessed are you when others revile you and persecute you and utter all kinds of evil against you falsely on my account

---> Verse 12: Rejoice and be glad, for your reward is great in heaven, for so they persecuted the prophets who were before you.


Those who are willing to endure harsh harsh or unfair treatment on account of faithfully following him can rejoice knowing they wil receive great rewards in heaven 

Jesus knew that many of his disciples would be unjustly persecuted for spreading the word of God

God has sent many prophets to the people of Israel to transmit messages to the people and many of them were persecuted, treated poorly and even killed

In this final beatitude, Jesus is telling us to experience joy when treated unfairly in his name because of the gifts that will be received for being persecuted in his name



---> Happiness

Modern culture often tells us that happiness comes through material things or the acquisition of things like fame and power

The beatitudes flip that and tell us that happiness comes through humility, dependence on God and living righteously which often ends up being very countercultural

The beatitudes tell us to focus on our heart and character, from which right action can then flow

They establish a framework for achieving happiness from the inside out

The beatitudes summarize kingdom values that shape decipleship and guide us towards obedience to God



